Parallelizing neural networks can significantly improve training performance in terms of speed and efficiency. There are several methods for parallelizing neural networks, including data parallelism, model parallelism, and pipeline parallelism.

Data parallelism involves splitting the dataset across multiple machines or processes, where each process trains the same model on a subset of the data. This is the most commonly used parallelization method for deep learning, as it is easy to implement and scale. However, it can result in loss of accuracy due to the stochastic nature of the gradient descent optimization method.

Model parallelism involves splitting the model across multiple machines or processes, where each process handles a subset of the model. This approach can provide better accuracy than data parallelism, as each process is training the same model on the entire dataset. However, it requires a more complex architecture and can be harder to implement and scale.

Pipeline parallelism involves splitting the model across multiple machines or processes, where each process handles a different stage of the pipeline (e.g., data preprocessing, model training, model evaluation). This approach can provide better accuracy than data parallelism, as each process is working on a different stage of the pipeline, but it can be harder to implement and scale.

```
(defn fibonacci
  ([n]
   (take n (lazy-seq (loop [a 0 b 1 acc []]
                      (if (zero? n)
                        acc
                        (recur (inc a) (inc b) (conj acc b)))))))
  ([n start]
   (loop [a start b start acc []]
     (take n (lazy-seq (recur (inc a) (inc b) (conj acc b)))))))
```

```
(take 10 (fibonacci 5 [1 2])) => [1 2 3 5 8]
```
Note that this solution uses recursion and lazy-seqs to compute the sequence as needed, rather than pre-computing the entire sequence in memory. This is a more efficient approach for larger values of `n`.
